Regarding your test suite: 100% code coverage on a one-line function means every line executed, not that every input class was tested. If your `isEven` tests only pass odd numbers, or if the assertions are inverted (e.g., `expect(isEven(3)).toBe(true)` -- which passes, but tests the wrong thing), coverage will be 100% and all tests will be green.

I understand the pushback, but the `% 2 === 1` check is mathematically an odd-number test. That is not a matter of interpretation. If these functions have been in production for a year without bug reports, the most likely explanations are: (1) `isEven` is not actually called on even numbers in your production paths, or (2) the callers compensate for the inverted result, or (3) the production version differs from what you posted here.

